SIMPLE: deject
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Deject
<hw>De*ject"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Dejected</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Dejecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>dejectus</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>dejicere</ets> to throw down; <ets>de-</ets> + <ets>jacere</ets>
to throw. See <er>Jet</er> a shooting forth.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
cast down.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Christ <qex>dejected</qex> himself even unto the hells.</q>
<rj><qau>Udall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes she <qex>dejects</qex> her eyes in a seeming civility;
and many mistake in her a cunning for a modest look.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cast down the spirits of; to dispirit; to
discourage; to dishearten.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor think, to die <qex>dejects</qex> my lofty mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Deject</ent>⟦br⟧

